node.text: DuPont State Recreational Forest in North Carolina is home to some of the most thrilling mountain bike trails. There are 80 miles of trails across 11,000 acres. Here, biking isn't just a sport. It's a way of life. CNN's @CoyWire joins the pack from @redwolftours for a perfect day on the mountain.

node.title: 'The skinniest, bumpiest, wildest ride I've been on in my life'

node.text: A striking photo shows a massive US military cargo plane carrying about 640 people from Kabul to Qatar on Sunday. Footage from Sunday night and Monday morning showed frenzied crowds seeking a route out of Afghanistan and trying to force their way onto any plane leaving Kabul airport after the Taliban swiftly took control of the country. (📸: Defense One/Reuters)

node.text: The US remains among the nations with the highest rate of new Covid-19 cases, driven mostly by a surge in the South, where many states are lagging in getting people vaccinated. node.text: “I stand squarely behind my decision. After 20 years, I’ve learned the hard way that there was never a good time to withdraw US forces,” President Biden said about Afghanistan. But he admitted, “The truth is, this did unfold more quickly than we had anticipated.”

All the friends I lost in Afghanistan- what were their deaths for? What was their sacrifice for if this was the end state?" Matt Zeller Afghanistan veteran CNN'.

node.text:
"Everybody in the community's going to be looking to see, how is history going to remember what we did over there?" said Tom Porter, an Afghanistan veteran and the executive vice president for government relations at Iraq and Afghanistan Veterans of America (IAVA). The images from Afghanistan are building a narrative that will shape veterans' views about the past 20 years, he said.⁠
⁠
(📸: Jim Huylebroek/The New York Times/Redux)

node.text: The Taliban are said to have seized at least 26 of Afghanistan's provincial capitals, including the capital of Kabul, since the beginning of August. Zaranj was the first provincial capital to fall.

When last they ruled, females were forbidden to attend school. They were shrouded in burqas, condemned to life at home and seen as male possessions." CNN Sam Kiley Senior International Correspondent'.

node.text: What will Afghanistan be like under the Taliban? The group's rise to power in the '90s paints a grim picture, especially for women, said CNN's Sam Kiley. Their goal is to impose their ultra-conservative interpretation of Islamic law and remove foreign influences from the country.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNN on August 16, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'WHO ARE THE TALIBAN AND HOW DID THEY TAKE CONTROL OF AFGHANISTAN so SWIFTLY? CNN'.

node.text: Taliban militants retook Afghanistan's capital on Sunday, almost two decades after they were driven from Kabul by US troops. Although Afghan security forces were well funded and well equipped, they put up little resistance as Taliban militants seized much of the country following the withdrawal of US troops beginning in early July.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNN on August 16, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'WHO ARE THE TALIBAN AND HOW DID THEY TAKE CONTROL OF AFGHANISTAN so SWIFTLY? CNN'.

Photo by CNN on August 16, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Who are the Taliban? Formed in 1994, the Taliban were made up of former Afghan resistance fighters, who fought the invading Soviet forces in the 1980s. After the Taliban captured Kabul in 1996, they put in place strict rules. Women had to wear head-t coverings, weren't allowed to study or work and were forbidden from traveling alone. TV, music and non-Islamic holidays were also banned. In the two decades since they were ousted from power, the Taliban have been waging an insurgency against the allied forces and the US-backed Afghan government. CNN WHO ARE THE TALIBAN?'.

Photo by CNN on August 16, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'What was their role in 9/11 terrorist attacks? The attack on September 11, 2001 that killed more than 2,700 people was orchestrated by al Qaeda leader Osama bin Laden. He was operating from inside of Taliban-controlled Afghanistan. Less than a month after the attack, the US and allied forces invaded Afghanistan, aiming to stop the Taliban from providing a safe-haven to al Qaeda and to stop al Qaeda from using Afghanistan as a base of operations for terrorist activities. CNN WHO ARE THE TALIBAN?'.

Photo by CNN on August 16, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Who are the leaders of the Taliban? The Taliban are led by Mawlawi Haibatullah Akhundzada a senior religious cleric from the Taliban's founding generation. He was named as the Taliban's leader in 2016 after the group's previous leader Mullah Akhtar Mohammad Mansour was killed in a US airstrike in Pakistan. Another key player is Mullah Abdul Ghani Baradar, the Talibar co-founder, who was released in 2013 after being captured in 2010 in Karachi, Pakistan's largest city. CNN WHO ARE THE TALIBAN?'.

Photo by CNN on August 16, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'What do the Taliban want? They have claimed to be committed to the peace process, an inclusive government, and willing to maintain some rights for women. A spokesman said women would still be allowed to continue their education and diplomats, journalists and non- -profits could continue operating in the country. But many observers worry that a return to Taliban rule is a return to the Afghanistan of two decades ago, when women's rights were severely restricted CNN WHO ARE THE TALIBAN?'.

Photo by CNN on August 16, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Why were the Taliban so strong against the Afghan forces? The US spent more than a trillion dollars in Afghanistan, training Afghan soldiers and police and providing them with equipment. But the Afghan forces sometimes lacked coordination and suffered from poor morale, said Carter Malkasian, a former senior adviser to the chairman of the US Joint Chiefs of Staff. The more defeats they had, the worse their morale became and the more emboldened the Taliban were. CNN WHO ARE THE TALIBAN?'.

Photo by CNN on August 16, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'What will happen next in Afghanistan? It's not clear. Lawmakers are pressing the Biden administration for answers and demanding information on how US intelligence could have so badly misjudged the situation on the ground. Biden remained at the Camp David presidential retreat Monday morning, amid rising pressure for him to address the nation on the crisis. CNN WHO ARE THE TALIBAN?'.
Photo by CNN on August 16, 2021. May be an image of 3 people, people standing and outdoors.

node.text:
It’s a sight that many Kabul residents thought would never come: Taliban fighters, relaxed and jubilant, standing outside the US embassy and presidential palace. The capital fell to the militant group in just a matter of hours on Sunday. The Taliban insurgents are now omnipresent, walking the streets with ease – and with American weapons in tow.

(📸: Wakil Kohsar/AFP/Getty Images, Rahmat Gul/AP, Reuters and Jim Huylebroek/The New York Times/Redux)

node.text:
Hundreds of people poured onto the tarmac at Kabul's international airport desperately seeking a route out of Afghanistan on Monday, after the Taliban's sudden seizure of power in the country. Footage shows the chaotic crowds trying to force their way onto any airplane leaving the city. Commercial flights from the airport have now been canceled and international airlines are scrambling to reroute flights away from Afghan airspace.
